  "articleSummary": "The article argues that fixed priority dropdowns (e.g., P1–P4) create a \"Priority Trap\" where teams endlessly inflate labels (P0, P00) instead of managing fluid, real-world priorities. It critiques this as \"Engineering Theater\" and distinguishes priority from severity, recommending unbounded numeric fields, multidimensional scoring, or dynamic methods like MoSCoW. The tone is humorous and analytical, using metaphors like the \"z-index war\" and \"Bizzaro Trophy Room\" to illustrate backlog decay. The intended audience includes developers, engineering managers, and product teams using tools like Jira.",
